1
00:00:06,000 --> 00:00:12,074


2
00:01:34,761 --> 00:01:37,972
[ Taps ]

3
00:02:20,598 --> 00:02:23,685
{y:i}[ Man Narrating ]
{y:i}Wake Island is a tiny dot
{y:i}in the midst of the Pacific,

4
00:02:23,768 --> 00:02:26,771
{y:i}4,254 air miles from San Francisco.

5
00:02:26,896 --> 00:02:31,359
{y:i}Until 1941, it was known
{y:i}only as a stepping stone
{y:i}for the Pan American Clippers.

6
00:02:31,484 --> 00:02:34,070
{y:i}In June of that year,
{y:i}the United States Marines landed.

7
00:02:34,195 --> 00:02:36,197
Present arms!

8
00:02:36,197 --> 00:02:39,284
[ Bugle Call ]

9
00:02:42,495 --> 00:02:46,791
{y:i}By the end of October, 1941,
{y:i}they had made progress.

10
00:02:46,875 --> 00:02:50,086
{y:i}Six five-inch naval guns like these
{y:i}had been emplaced.

11
00:02:50,295 --> 00:02:53,798
{y:i}In addition, they had 12 mobile
{y:i}three-inch antiaircraft guns.

12
00:02:53,882 --> 00:02:58,762
{y:i}A squadron of 12 Grumann F4F3's,
{y:i}nicknamed "wildcats," ere based at Wake.

13
00:02:58,887 --> 00:03:03,975
{y:i}And the 385 officers and men
{y:i}of the First Defense Battalion,
{y:i}United States Marine Corps...

14
00:03:04,059 --> 00:03:07,896
{y:i}were constantly on the alert,
{y:i}patrolling the skies daily.

15
00:03:09,481 --> 00:03:11,858
[ Indistinct Shouts ]

16
00:03:19,491 --> 00:03:23,662
Left shoulder arms!

17
00:03:23,787 --> 00:03:27,374
Right shoulder arms!
{y:i}Late in 1941,
{y:i}Headquarters Marine Corps...

18
00:03:27,499 --> 00:03:30,669
{y:i}assigned a new commanding officer
{y:i}to this tiny garrison.
{y:i}To the rear, march!

19
00:03:30,794 --> 00:03:35,298
{y:i}His name:Major Geoffirey Caton.
{y:i}His record:long and active.

20
00:03:35,298 --> 00:03:39,094
{y:i}In Pearl Harbor on a November morning,
{y:i}Major Caton makes his farewells.

21
00:03:40,470 --> 00:03:42,681
{y:i}[ Girl ]
{y:i}With the compliments
{y:i}of your daughter, sir.

22
00:03:42,764 --> 00:03:45,684
Well! Say, this is something.

23
00:03:45,767 --> 00:03:47,686
Open it.

24
00:03:47,769 --> 00:03:51,272
{y:i}"To Daddy from Cynthia,
{y:i}November, 1941. "

25
00:03:51,398 --> 00:03:54,067
It cost me
an awful lot of money.
I'll bet it did.

26
00:03:54,192 --> 00:03:56,778
Practically all my savings.

27
00:03:56,986 --> 00:04:01,199
You know, you are getting a little thin.
Better catch up on your ice cream sodas.

28
00:04:01,282 --> 00:04:03,660
Thanks, Daddy.
I'll be gone a long time.

29
00:04:03,785 --> 00:04:07,497
Thanks a lot!
Well, what goes with thanks?

30
00:04:09,791 --> 00:04:12,460
Where is this old
Wake Island, anyhow?

31
00:04:12,460 --> 00:04:15,672
Oh, it's just a little strip of sand
with a lot of water around it.

32
00:04:16,881 --> 00:04:18,883
Good-byes are awful, aren't they?

33
00:04:18,967 --> 00:04:21,970
Well, you let yourself in for a lot of them
when you married a marine.

34
00:04:22,095 --> 00:04:24,180
I know.

35
00:04:24,180 --> 00:04:27,684
What, again?
I'd feel like this
if you were going away overnight.

36
00:04:27,767 --> 00:04:30,478
Next time I leave,
I'm gonna bring a bucket.

37
00:04:30,687 --> 00:04:33,064
Here's where I leave ya.
Good-bye.

38
00:04:33,189 --> 00:04:36,192
Good-bye.
Thanks for showin' me the town.

39
00:04:36,359 --> 00:04:39,070
{y:i}Aloha nui kako.
Oh, save it till I come back.

40
00:04:39,070 --> 00:04:41,072
Here. Thanks, Charlie.

41
00:05:00,592 --> 00:05:02,594
[ Sobs ]

42
00:05:12,687 --> 00:05:14,689
Mr. McCloskey!

43
00:05:16,066 --> 00:05:18,068
Mr. McCloskey!

44
00:05:19,361 --> 00:05:21,863
Good morning.
Oh. Morning.

45
00:05:21,988 --> 00:05:24,574
I don't suppose you got
a bar on this boat.

46
00:05:24,699 --> 00:05:26,660
Can't even offer you
a cold shower.

47
00:05:26,785 --> 00:05:29,871
Have we got there yet?
No. We won't be in
for some time.

48
00:05:29,996 --> 00:05:32,582
Would you like
to slick up a little?

49
00:05:32,665 --> 00:05:35,460
Look, General, you're a soldier
and I'm a civilian.

50
00:05:35,585 --> 00:05:38,797
I got a government contract
with a mighty important job to do,

51
00:05:38,880 --> 00:05:41,758
but there's not one word in it
about takin' orders from brass hats.

52
00:05:41,883 --> 00:05:44,678
That goes for suggestions
about shavin' too.

53
00:05:44,678 --> 00:05:47,263
Call me when we get there.
That's all I want from you.

54
00:05:51,059 --> 00:05:53,770
Let me take another look
at our future home.

55
00:06:06,366 --> 00:06:10,286
Yes, sir, I can see 'em
in me mind's eye--

56
00:06:10,495 --> 00:06:14,791
big ones, little ones--
all guzzlin' and gruntin'...

57
00:06:14,874 --> 00:06:16,793
{y:i}and puttin'on weight.

58
00:06:16,876 --> 00:06:19,796
{y:i}Yes, sir. Hundreds of'em.
Hundreds of which?

59
00:06:21,089 --> 00:06:22,966
Hogs.

60
00:06:23,091 --> 00:06:24,968
Yes, sir.

61
00:06:25,093 --> 00:06:29,389
That's what the ex-wrestling champ
of the Pacific Fleet has finally decided on.

62
00:06:29,389 --> 00:06:31,391
Outta this outfit and into hogs.

63
00:06:31,391 --> 00:06:33,476
{y:i}That's me.
Last week it was turkeys.

64
00:06:33,560 --> 00:06:36,896
Turks is out.
I just read a book.

65
00:06:36,896 --> 00:06:40,358
Turks has got 2 49 pages
of diseases.

66
00:06:40,483 --> 00:06:42,485
{y:i}[ Plane Engines Droning ]

67
00:06:42,569 --> 00:06:44,779
There she goes.
The old Clipper.

68
00:06:51,286 --> 00:06:53,997
Ya great big beautiful
sweetheart, you.

69
00:06:54,080 --> 00:06:57,083
A week, and I'll be aboard one of them.

70
00:06:57,083 --> 00:07:01,379
Mr. Aloysius K. Randall,
United States citizen, tourist deluxe.

71
00:07:01,379 --> 00:07:04,090
Monkeys like you
don't rate no Clippers.

72
00:07:04,174 --> 00:07:07,093
Well, I got the dough,
and I got the old man's say-so.

73
00:07:07,093 --> 00:07:09,387
Don't you worry, bub.
I'll be on it, all right.

74
00:07:09,387 --> 00:07:13,475
Hey, look, Smacksie.
Right here I got 1 0 bucks,
and I'm gonna bet you the whole--

75
00:07:13,558 --> 00:07:16,978
Where at did you
ever get 1 0 bucks?
I got it, all right.

76
00:07:17,062 --> 00:07:19,564
And right now that 1 0 bucks
is sayin' that you don't leave.

77
00:07:19,689 --> 00:07:22,359
'Cause why?
'Cause you'll ship over, that's why.

78
00:07:22,484 --> 00:07:26,196
Ahhh. A float!

79
00:07:27,572 --> 00:07:29,491
For me.

80
00:07:39,167 --> 00:07:41,878
Oh, boy! One of them
hammer and sickles!

81
00:07:41,961 --> 00:07:44,089
Let me have a look at it!
Get your hands away.

82
00:07:44,172 --> 00:07:46,466
I seen it first!
Yeah, well, I got it first!

83
00:07:46,466 --> 00:07:48,968
Gimme that!
Let go!

84
00:07:49,094 --> 00:07:52,597
Why, you baboon-faced, no-good--

85
00:07:52,680 --> 00:07:55,266
You see, you left yourself
wide open for an arm lock.

86
00:07:55,392 --> 00:07:58,395
I don't wanna hear any of that
wrestling talk! I just wanna
punch you right in the nose!

87
00:07:58,478 --> 00:08:00,897
Okay. There it is. Go ahead.
All right!

88
00:08:00,897 --> 00:08:03,983
[ Bugle Call ]
Chow.

89
00:08:03,983 --> 00:08:06,361
[ Whistles ]
Come on, Skipper! Come on!

90
00:08:11,866 --> 00:08:14,786
{y:i}Hey, you two. Just a minute.

91
00:08:14,869 --> 00:08:17,997
What have you two guys
been up to?
We were swimmin', Sarge.

92
00:08:17,997 --> 00:08:21,376
Swimmin'?
Yeah. You owe me a medal.
I just saved his life.

93
00:08:21,459 --> 00:08:24,879
That bugler saved yours, pal.
All right, all right.
Get in the line.

94
00:08:27,590 --> 00:08:30,885
Here we go.
Good old stew.

95
00:08:33,471 --> 00:08:35,390
What do you think I am?
A canary?

96
00:08:35,473 --> 00:08:38,476
Move on, my friend.
All right, wise guy.

97
00:08:38,560 --> 00:08:41,479
One of these days you're going to find out
what I got these two stripes for.

98
00:08:41,563 --> 00:08:44,691
{y:i}Heil!
Who said that?

99
00:08:45,775 --> 00:08:48,695
Somebody around here's a wise guy.

100
00:08:48,778 --> 00:08:51,197
Only one of these days
I'm going to catch up with him, see,

101
00:08:51,197 --> 00:08:56,161
and he's going to find out
that just because my name is Goebbels,
that doesn't make me a heinie.

102
00:08:56,286 --> 00:09:00,373
My folks was Holland Dutch,
and if anybody doesn't think so,
all he's got to do is speak up.

103
00:09:00,498 --> 00:09:03,293
Do you understand?
But I didn't say anything, Corporal.

104
00:09:03,376 --> 00:09:08,089
Maybe you did
and maybe you didn't.
Anyway, I'm warning you.

105
00:09:09,382 --> 00:09:11,760
{y:i}Heil!
Who said that?

106
00:09:14,387 --> 00:09:16,389
{y:i}Heil!

107
00:09:18,892 --> 00:09:20,769
Who said that?

108
00:09:20,894 --> 00:09:24,689
Don't let 'em get you so hot, Corp.
You'll spoil your chow.

109
00:09:30,695 --> 00:09:32,864
All right, Corporal.
Sit down and eat.

110
00:09:32,989 --> 00:09:35,283
Sparks! Where have you been?

111
00:09:35,367 --> 00:09:38,286
Just got off duty.
Oh, I got some hot news for you.

112
00:09:38,370 --> 00:09:40,664
The new C.O.
will be here in an hour.
What's his name?

113
00:09:40,789 --> 00:09:43,792
Caton.
Caton?
Must be Artillery Caton.

114
00:09:43,875 --> 00:09:46,586
That guy eats 'em alive.
Tough, huh?

115
00:09:46,669 --> 00:09:49,798
He had me in and outta the brig
so much, I wore it out.

116
00:09:49,881 --> 00:09:53,677
Boys, the honeymoon's over.
From now on, you're marines.

117
00:10:29,087 --> 00:10:31,464
Hello, Jeff.
How are you, Johnson?
Glad to see you.

118
00:10:31,589 --> 00:10:33,466
Have a good trip?
Fine, thank you.

119
00:10:33,591 --> 00:10:35,593
Well, nice to see you again.
Thank you.

120
00:10:35,593 --> 00:10:38,388
Our commanding officer,
Commander Roberts, Major Caton.

121
00:10:38,471 --> 00:10:41,766
Reporting, sir.
Major, we're glad to have you
share our exile with us.

122
00:10:41,891 --> 00:10:44,060
Thank you, sir.
Nielson of Pan American.

123
00:10:44,185 --> 00:10:46,187
How do you do, sir?
Parkman, our doctor.

124
00:10:46,271 --> 00:10:48,273
Play bridge, Major?
I play at it, sir.

125
00:10:48,273 --> 00:10:50,275
Certainly need new blood, sir.
Thanks.

126
00:10:50,275 --> 00:10:52,277
Patrick, our squadron commander.
Happy to know you, sir.

127
00:10:52,277 --> 00:10:54,279
And this is--
I know the major.

128
00:10:54,279 --> 00:10:57,782
Hello, Lewis. How are you?
Captain Patrick, I brought you
a new man-- Lieutenant Cameron.

129
00:10:57,782 --> 00:10:59,784
Bruce Cameron?
Yes, sir.

130
00:10:59,784 --> 00:11:02,078
Come along, Patrick.
I'll introduce you.
I know his father.

131
00:11:02,162 --> 00:11:04,080
Right, sir.
Excuse us.

132
00:11:04,164 --> 00:11:07,292
Excuse us, Mr. Nielson.
There's a guard waiting for the major.
Certainly.

133
00:11:07,375 --> 00:11:10,462
Guard, front!

134
00:11:10,587 --> 00:11:13,673
{y:i}[ Bugle Call ]

135
00:11:13,882 --> 00:11:16,259
{y:i}Guard, face front!

136
00:11:16,259 --> 00:11:19,179
{y:i}Present arms!

137
00:11:26,895 --> 00:11:29,397
Lower arms!

138
00:11:29,397 --> 00:11:31,399
Left face!

139
00:11:32,859 --> 00:11:36,196
{y:i}Right shoulder arms!

140
00:11:36,196 --> 00:11:38,198
{y:i}Forward march!

141
00:11:38,281 --> 00:11:40,283
Mr. McCloskey?
Yeah.

142
00:11:40,367 --> 00:11:43,161
I'm Hogan. Pete Hogan.
Your foreman.
How are ya?

143
00:11:43,286 --> 00:11:47,290
I'm glad there's somebody
here to meet me, although I know
I don't rate no fancy parade.

144
00:11:47,374 --> 00:11:50,877
Well, if I'd thought of it,
I'd have had some of our boys
lined up for you... with shovels.

145
00:11:50,877 --> 00:11:54,172
How you been making out?
Oh, fair to middlin',
Mr. McCloskey.

146
00:11:54,297 --> 00:11:56,883
Built quarters for the men and
spotted some of the ground work.

147
00:11:56,966 --> 00:12:00,387
Maybe not as much as you'd expect,
but we've sorta been waitin'
around for you.

148
00:12:00,387 --> 00:12:05,475
I'll take a look at what you've done, then
I'd like to meet the crew and get acquainted.
All right.

149
00:12:05,475 --> 00:12:07,560
And you've gotta get
that excavating finished.

150
00:12:07,686 --> 00:12:10,980
You better work three shifts.
I wanna start pouring concrete by Thursday.

151
00:12:10,980 --> 00:12:13,358
Oh, that'll be tough.
Maybe so. Do it anyway.

152
00:12:13,483 --> 00:12:16,277
I've never been late with a contract yet,
not even a government one,

153
00:12:16,361 --> 00:12:18,780
and I'm not gonna start in
on this bird sanctuary.

154
00:12:18,989 --> 00:12:20,990
Mr. McCloskey.
Yes?

155
00:12:23,576 --> 00:12:25,870
So the major wants me
to have dinner with him.

156
00:12:25,995 --> 00:12:28,665
Tell him I'm too busy.
Yes, sir.

157
00:12:28,790 --> 00:12:31,167
That's another thing.
You guys have probably noticed...

158
00:12:31,292 --> 00:12:34,587
this sand pile is stiff with brass hats
trying to play soldier.

159
00:12:34,587 --> 00:12:38,466
If any of'em get in your hair,
tell 'em to come see me. That's all.

160
00:12:40,093 --> 00:12:43,388
[ Reveille ]

161
00:12:51,271 --> 00:12:54,399
[ Skipper Barking ]

162
00:12:57,569 --> 00:12:59,571
Good morning, dear.

163
00:13:01,990 --> 00:13:06,161
The next time I get a furlough,
I'm gonna hire a bugler
to blow reveille for me.

164
00:13:06,286 --> 00:13:09,164
Why?
'Cause when he sounds off,
I'm gonna get up,

165
00:13:09,289 --> 00:13:11,583
beat his brains out,
then go back to sleep.

166
00:13:11,583 --> 00:13:13,877
Buglers ain't got no brains.

167
00:13:13,960 --> 00:13:16,087
Comin' from you,
that's somethin'.

168
00:13:17,088 --> 00:13:20,091
I'm glad I don't have to take
that guff from you much longer.

169
00:13:20,175 --> 00:13:22,594
Seven more days, and all
you'll see is my tail feathers.

170
00:13:22,677 --> 00:13:25,889
I still got that 10 bucks,
and it still says you don't leave.

171
00:13:25,972 --> 00:13:29,059
Do you really
wanna lose 10 bucks?

172
00:13:29,267 --> 00:13:31,895
Put up or shut up.
Okay.

173
00:13:35,065 --> 00:13:36,983
There.

174
00:13:37,067 --> 00:13:39,861
It's a bet.
Wait a minute.
Where's your dough?

175
00:13:39,986 --> 00:13:41,863
I got it, all right.
Don't worry.

176
00:13:41,988 --> 00:13:44,699
Let me see it.
It's very dangerous to leave
money lyin' around here.

177
00:13:44,783 --> 00:13:46,868
The captain's holding it for me.

178
00:13:48,495 --> 00:13:50,872
Oh, so you don't trust me, huh?

179
00:13:57,379 --> 00:14:00,173
Well, look what we have here.

180
00:14:00,298 --> 00:14:02,592
Well, bless their
sleepy little heads.

181
00:14:02,592 --> 00:14:06,262
Maybe we been talking too loud.
Yeah. Shh.

182
00:14:11,393 --> 00:14:13,895
[ Laughing ]

183
00:14:15,188 --> 00:14:17,982
I hope they can swim.

184
00:14:17,982 --> 00:14:20,068
Attention!

185
00:14:22,487 --> 00:14:26,783
What's this, Sergeant?
That's no way to camouflage a gun.

186
00:14:26,783 --> 00:14:29,494
Whose is it?
Mine, sir.

187
00:14:29,577 --> 00:14:32,580
How long have you been
in the marines, son?
Six months, sir.

188
00:14:32,664 --> 00:14:35,166
That's long enough to know better.

189
00:14:36,584 --> 00:14:39,462
That's Artillery Caton, all right.
Snoopin' around this early, huh?

190
00:14:39,587 --> 00:14:41,798
Things used to be so nice here.

191
00:14:44,759 --> 00:14:46,678
Attention!

192
00:14:53,893 --> 00:14:55,895
This is it.

193
00:14:55,895 --> 00:14:58,898
{y:i}[ Caton ]
{y:i}All of it?
{y:i}All of it.

194
00:14:58,898 --> 00:15:01,693
{y:i}You could hardly call it
{y:i}Gibraltar, could you?

195
00:15:03,194 --> 00:15:05,989
{y:i}Twenty-one feet
{y:i}at its highest elevation.

196
00:15:06,072 --> 00:15:10,493
{y:i}And in any sort of a breeze,
{y:i}my friend, it all shakes.

197
00:15:10,577 --> 00:15:13,663
{y:i}Well, sir, if the navy has survived,
{y:i}I guess the marines can.

198
00:15:13,788 --> 00:15:15,999
{y:i}You know, commander,

199
00:15:15,999 --> 00:15:19,461
{y:i}my outfit's supposed to be
{y:i}a defense battalion.

200
00:15:19,586 --> 00:15:23,965
{y:i}I don't see much to defend here.
{y:i}As a matter of fact,
{y:i}not much to defend it with.

201
00:15:24,090 --> 00:15:26,676
Only marines.

202
00:15:26,676 --> 00:15:30,096
Well, now that you've landed,
you'd better get the situation in hand.

203
00:15:30,180 --> 00:15:33,975
We will, sir. Starting straightaway.
I have an inspection in 10 minutes.

204
00:15:34,059 --> 00:15:36,269
All right. Let's shove off.
Right.

205
00:15:37,395 --> 00:15:40,065
[ Humming ]
{y:i}[ Bugle Blaring ]

206
00:15:40,273 --> 00:15:42,859
You look better than Joe, Skipper.

207
00:15:42,984 --> 00:15:45,987
[ Continues Humming ]

208
00:15:49,074 --> 00:15:51,659
Inspection, 10 minutes.

209
00:15:51,659 --> 00:15:55,789
Listen, slap-happy, you'd
better cut out the spring song
and stand by for inspection.

210
00:15:55,789 --> 00:15:58,166
Why, that ain't spring, Sarge.
That's love.

211
00:15:58,291 --> 00:16:02,295
Trouble with that guy,
he ain't got no finer instincts.
That's how you get to be a sergeant.

212
00:16:04,089 --> 00:16:06,966
The dumber them guys are,
the more stripes they give 'em.

213
00:16:07,092 --> 00:16:09,094
You oughta look like a zebra.

214
00:16:09,094 --> 00:16:12,180
Always got an answer, ain't ya?
[ Chuckles ]

215
00:16:12,263 --> 00:16:14,391
Hey, hey! What's that thing?

216
00:16:14,474 --> 00:16:16,976
That ain't no thing.
It's a dame.

217
00:16:17,060 --> 00:16:19,187
[ Wolf Whistle ]
Could be.

218
00:16:19,270 --> 00:16:21,481
You got it upside-down. There.

219
00:16:21,564 --> 00:16:25,276
I like it better this way.
Listen, soldier. When you act
disrespectful about her,

220
00:16:25,276 --> 00:16:29,572
you're actin' disrespectful about the dame
what's practically Mrs. Aloysius K. Randall.

221
00:16:29,698 --> 00:16:33,076
And I don't like it, see.
Why, you thick-headed clunk.

222
00:16:33,159 --> 00:16:35,870
You mean to tell me you're thinkin'
about gettin' married?

223
00:16:39,165 --> 00:16:42,585
You mean to tell me you've found
a dame that would marry you?

224
00:16:43,586 --> 00:16:46,089
The nuptials is bein' performed
New Year's mornin'.

225
00:16:46,172 --> 00:16:48,675
Besides, dumber lookin' clunks
than me get married.

226
00:16:48,883 --> 00:16:51,761
Name one.
Well--

227
00:16:51,886 --> 00:16:53,888
Why, you--
Get your--

228
00:16:53,888 --> 00:16:57,183
{y:i}-[ Bugle Call ]
- Hey, come on, you guys! Inspection.

229
00:16:57,267 --> 00:17:00,478
Saved by the bugle again.
Saved from what?

230
00:17:00,478 --> 00:17:02,689
From this.

231
00:17:02,772 --> 00:17:05,066
Oh, there they go again.
Aw, fellas, look!

232
00:17:05,066 --> 00:17:07,360
Come on. Cut it out!
You're gonna get us in a jam again.

233
00:17:07,485 --> 00:17:09,863
Act your age, will ya?
You'll get us in more trouble!

234
00:17:09,863 --> 00:17:11,990
Get away!

235
00:17:11,990 --> 00:17:14,492
{y:i}[ Skipper Barking ]

236
00:17:22,292 --> 00:17:25,170
Attention!
Straighten up here.

237
00:17:25,170 --> 00:17:28,381
- Who's responsible for this?
- [ Both ] Me, sir.

238
00:17:28,465 --> 00:17:31,760
Who are these men, Sergeant?
Privates Randall and Doyle, sir.

239
00:17:31,885 --> 00:17:35,472
Haven't we met before?
Yes, sir. China Station, sir.

240
00:17:35,597 --> 00:17:38,892
I suppose you've already discovered,
Randall, that we have no brig here.

241
00:17:38,975 --> 00:17:40,894
Yes, sir.

242
00:17:40,977 --> 00:17:43,480
{y:i}You know, I haven't got
{y:i}much faith in brigs, anyway.
No, sir.

243
00:17:43,563 --> 00:17:46,066
Putting a marine in the brig
is a waste of good manpower.

244
00:17:46,066 --> 00:17:48,985
That's right, sir.
I'll see these men
in the morning, Sergeant.

245
00:17:49,069 --> 00:17:51,488
In the meantime,
I'll try and think of some way...

246
00:17:51,571 --> 00:17:55,658
of diverting your surplus energy
into more useful and constructive channels.

247
00:17:55,784 --> 00:17:58,286
Yes, sir.

248
00:17:59,996 --> 00:18:02,874
I don't like the sound of that
"constructive channels" stuff.

249
00:18:02,874 --> 00:18:05,877
No, sir. Aw, what am I sayin'?

250
00:18:17,597 --> 00:18:22,560
Hey, if this is a sample of Caton's
constructive channels, give me the brig.

251
00:18:22,686 --> 00:18:25,063
What are we diggin' here, anyway?
A slit trench.

252
00:18:25,188 --> 00:18:28,274
Huh?
Bomb shelter for air raids.

253
00:18:28,358 --> 00:18:30,568
What bombs and which air raids?

254
00:18:39,286 --> 00:18:41,579
- What's on your mind, pal?
- Oh, nothing.

255
00:18:41,663 --> 00:18:45,291
I was just wondering what would happen
if marines had to do a good day's work.

256
00:18:47,794 --> 00:18:50,588
What do you suppose they give you
for bustin' a civilian?

257
00:18:50,672 --> 00:18:52,882
In self-defense?
Naw,just bustin' him.

258
00:18:52,966 --> 00:18:55,468
With or without provocation?
Both.

259
00:18:55,593 --> 00:18:58,888
For bustin' a guy like that, I guess
they'd give you the Medal of Honor.

260
00:18:58,972 --> 00:19:00,765
Come on. Back to nature.

261
00:19:11,776 --> 00:19:13,778
Hey, what's happened here?

262
00:19:13,862 --> 00:19:15,989
Pete just passed out.
Too much sun.

263
00:19:15,989 --> 00:19:19,576
Get him over to the hospital.
I'll take charge while you
get another man for the tractor.

264
00:19:19,659 --> 00:19:21,578
Okay, Mac.

265
00:19:26,958 --> 00:19:30,587
{y:i}[ Air Raid Siren Blaring ]

266
00:19:34,466 --> 00:19:38,386
Hey, what is this? Hogan!

267
00:19:41,681 --> 00:19:44,059
{y:i}[ Siren Stops ]
Hey, Hogan!

268
00:19:44,184 --> 00:19:46,561
What goes on?
Orders, Mr. McCloskey.

269
00:19:46,686 --> 00:19:50,774
Whose orders? For what?
Civilian air raid drill.
Here. Here it is.

270
00:19:50,774 --> 00:19:54,486
"Approach of enemy aircraft will be
signaled by long blast on claxon horn.

271
00:19:54,569 --> 00:19:57,280
All civilian workers
will thereupon take cover."

272
00:19:57,364 --> 00:19:59,866
Where'd you get that?
Major Caton's office.

273
00:19:59,991 --> 00:20:04,662
Major Caton! Well,
I might as well shake that guy
out of my hair right now.

274
00:20:04,871 --> 00:20:08,291
It's my job to keep those men out there
working and the machinery rolling.

275
00:20:08,375 --> 00:20:12,796
If they're gonna run in the bushes
every time a brass hat toots a horn,
I'm gonna wind up behind the eight ball.

276
00:20:12,796 --> 00:20:16,299
The responsibility for the life of every man
on this island is invested in us.

277
00:20:16,299 --> 00:20:19,177
In times like these,
air raid drill is necessary.

278
00:20:19,260 --> 00:20:22,889
In times like these, it's necessary
for you guys to let me get my job finished.

279
00:20:22,973 --> 00:20:26,267
We're just as anxious as you are
for you to finish your job.

280
00:20:26,267 --> 00:20:29,979
Right. Then quit stampedin' my men
with that peewee auto horn
and let me get to it!

281
00:20:30,063 --> 00:20:33,483
Everybody must participate
in the air raid drill.

282
00:20:33,566 --> 00:20:36,569
{y:i}There will be no exceptions.
So it's a must, is it?

283
00:20:36,695 --> 00:20:38,571
Exactly.

284
00:20:40,198 --> 00:20:43,576
Well, General, the first man of mine that
ducks in the bushes when the horn blows...

285
00:20:43,576 --> 00:20:46,079
is gonna get a two-by-four
over his head.

286
00:20:46,162 --> 00:20:48,498
Mr. McCloskey!

287
00:20:50,667 --> 00:20:54,963
Sir, I'm going to give you
a bit of advice.

288
00:20:55,088 --> 00:20:58,675
Orders from the United States
Navy Department will be obeyed!

289
00:21:10,478 --> 00:21:13,189
{y:i}[ Engine Rewing ]

290
00:21:20,572 --> 00:21:23,992
In trouble?
[ Both Laughing ]

291
00:21:25,160 --> 00:21:27,287
Yes, and I want you guys
to push me out.

292
00:21:27,370 --> 00:21:29,873
[ Laughing ]
Did I hear right?

293
00:21:29,873 --> 00:21:33,460
- Yeah. But it ain't right.
- Come on. Get up outta there.

294
00:21:33,585 --> 00:21:36,379
On your way, bubble puss,
or I'll pat ya with me shovel.

295
00:21:36,463 --> 00:21:39,466
Are you gonna come out peacefully,
or do I have to drag you out?

296
00:21:39,466 --> 00:21:43,386
You start swingin' right now, bud.
I'll be with you in a second.

297
00:21:43,470 --> 00:21:45,680
No, no, no.
This one's mine.
I'll flip you for it.

298
00:21:45,764 --> 00:21:48,475
- Well, okay.
- Hurry up. Make up your mind.
I got work to do.

299
00:21:48,558 --> 00:21:50,894
Call it.
Heads.

300
00:21:50,977 --> 00:21:55,482
Tails. Candy from a baby.

301
00:22:00,195 --> 00:22:02,197
You ain't doin' so good,
Joey boy.

302
00:22:02,280 --> 00:22:05,158
Well, the sun got in my eyes.
Yeah, I heard it hit.

303
00:22:12,290 --> 00:22:15,668
Time was, Joe,
when you hit a guy, he stayed hit.

304
00:22:17,170 --> 00:22:20,382
That's it, Joe. Attaboy.
Break his legs off!.

305
00:22:25,595 --> 00:22:28,473
What are you wavin' at him for?
Grab a hold of him!

306
00:22:33,061 --> 00:22:36,189
{y:i}[ Vehicle Approaching ]
Watch it, Joe. The old man.

307
00:22:47,575 --> 00:22:49,661
What's that truck doing here?

308
00:22:49,786 --> 00:22:52,372
Well, sir, uh,
just passing through, sir.

309
00:22:52,580 --> 00:22:54,499
Whose is it?

310
00:22:54,582 --> 00:22:56,459
It's mine.

311
00:22:56,668 --> 00:23:01,965
Oh, Mr. McCloskey.
Had an accident?

312
00:23:02,966 --> 00:23:07,762
Yes, I had an accident, all right.
I tripped. Why?

313
00:23:07,887 --> 00:23:10,682
Well, can I be
of any assistance?
No.

314
00:23:12,684 --> 00:23:14,686
Carry on.

315
00:23:24,070 --> 00:23:26,072
From Commander Roberts, sir.

316
00:23:30,368 --> 00:23:33,288
"Special Japanese envoy
will arrive on the Clipper."

317
00:23:36,583 --> 00:23:40,962
Gentlemen,
it is my great privilege...

318
00:23:40,962 --> 00:23:45,467
to propose a toast
to that great executive...

319
00:23:45,592 --> 00:23:48,178
of your great democracy...

320
00:23:48,178 --> 00:23:52,098
whose lasting peace
it is my country's...

321
00:23:52,182 --> 00:23:55,185
greatest wish to preserve.

322
00:23:55,268 --> 00:23:57,896
Gentlemen, I give you...

323
00:23:57,979 --> 00:24:02,359
the president of the United States,
Franklin Delano Roosevelt.

324
00:24:02,484 --> 00:24:04,361
Hear, hear!
Thank you.

325
00:24:05,695 --> 00:24:08,573
Gentlemen, I give you
His Imperial Majesty,

326
00:24:08,698 --> 00:24:11,159
Emperor Hirohito of Japan.

327
00:24:17,791 --> 00:24:21,961
As you all know,
I am on my way to Washington.

328
00:24:22,963 --> 00:24:26,675
With me I carry
a message from my emperor...

329
00:24:27,759 --> 00:24:30,595
to the president of your country.

330
00:24:30,678 --> 00:24:34,599
Gentlemen,
it is a message of peace.

331
00:24:38,395 --> 00:24:41,064
I regret very much to say...

332
00:24:41,189 --> 00:24:44,859
that between my people
and your people...

333
00:24:44,984 --> 00:24:48,279
there have been some
small misunderstandings.

334
00:24:48,363 --> 00:24:52,575
But it is, therefore,
my emperor's desire...

335
00:24:52,659 --> 00:24:57,789
{y:i}that I show to your president
{y:i}the heart of the Japanese people.

336
00:24:57,872 --> 00:25:01,084
{y:i}And I do solemnly swear...

337
00:25:01,084 --> 00:25:06,089
that in that heart he will find
no thought of war...

338
00:25:06,172 --> 00:25:10,593
but, rather, a yearning
for lasting peace.

339
00:25:11,886 --> 00:25:14,097
Therefore, gentlemen,

340
00:25:14,097 --> 00:25:18,393
I ask that you wish me Godspeed.

341
00:25:49,090 --> 00:25:53,470
On this clear and peaceful
Sunday morning, December 7, 1941,

342
00:25:53,470 --> 00:25:56,765
as countless thousands of you
are enjoying the security of your homes,

343
00:25:56,890 --> 00:26:01,061
a great drama of U.S. Japanese relations
is moving swiftly to a climax.

344
00:26:01,186 --> 00:26:03,980
In the State Department,
at this precise moment,

345
00:26:03,980 --> 00:26:06,858
Mr. Cordell Hull is receiving
for a final interview...

346
00:26:06,858 --> 00:26:11,071
Ambassador Nomura and
Special Envoy Saburo Kurusu of Japan.

347
00:26:11,196 --> 00:26:13,573
It is understood that
Special Envoy Kurusu...

348
00:26:13,698 --> 00:26:16,576
has brought with him
Emperor Hirohito's reply...

349
00:26:16,576 --> 00:26:20,872
to President Roosevelt's note
protesting Japan's aggression
in the Far East.

350
00:26:20,872 --> 00:26:24,292
This morning Envoy Kurusu stated
that his emperor's message would,

351
00:26:24,376 --> 00:26:26,961
he was confident,
solve the Pacific problem.

352
00:26:27,087 --> 00:26:29,881
So today, for the first time
in many anxious months,

353
00:26:29,964 --> 00:26:34,677
a new note of optimism and hope
marks the tempo of the Washington scene.

354
00:26:34,677 --> 00:26:38,682
Why don't you quit
listenin' to that guff?
Get somethin' romantic.

355
00:26:39,766 --> 00:26:42,477
Myrtle, honey, I'm on my way.

356
00:26:42,560 --> 00:26:45,271
So you're really gonna go, huh?
Yep.

357
00:26:45,397 --> 00:26:47,899
Oh, and by the way,
you owe me 10 bucks.

358
00:26:47,983 --> 00:26:52,195
You haven't left yet.
I ain't dressed up for no
Sunday morning inspection.

359
00:26:52,278 --> 00:26:55,198
One look at you in that outfit,
and the old man'll throw the book at you.

360
00:26:55,281 --> 00:26:57,659
Well, I got his permission,
see, Mr. Smart Guy.

361
00:26:57,784 --> 00:27:01,788
Mr. Randall Caton says,
"You are now a gentleman of leisure.

362
00:27:01,871 --> 00:27:05,792
And if you wish to travel in formal attire,"
he says, "it's okay by me."

363
00:27:05,875 --> 00:27:09,671
Mr. Aloysius K. Randall, Esquire,
back in circulation.

364
00:27:09,796 --> 00:27:11,965
How do you like that?

365
00:27:17,178 --> 00:27:20,390
Hey, what's your hurry?

366
00:27:20,473 --> 00:27:22,475
The Clipper doesn't leave
just this minute.

367
00:27:22,684 --> 00:27:27,564
Well, I'm gonna have Sparks radio Myrtle
to lay in a supply of orange blossoms.

368
00:27:33,361 --> 00:27:36,781
World, here I come!

369
00:27:38,658 --> 00:27:41,494
{y:i}[ Men Laughing, Whistling ]

370
00:27:41,494 --> 00:27:44,873
[ Men Chattering ]

371
00:27:44,873 --> 00:27:49,669
Any of you guys don't like this hat,
you can come out here
and try to knock it off.

372
00:27:49,794 --> 00:27:52,589
That includes you.
I think you're beautiful.

373
00:27:52,672 --> 00:27:54,883
Go on. On your way, civilian.

374
00:27:54,966 --> 00:27:57,969
[ Men Laughing ]
Hey, Smacksie.

375
00:27:58,094 --> 00:28:00,889
[ Chattering Continues ]

376
00:28:02,098 --> 00:28:04,059
Hey, Sparks.
Yeah?

377
00:28:04,059 --> 00:28:07,771
How do you spell "nuptials"?
Nuptials? N-U-P-T--

378
00:28:07,771 --> 00:28:10,190
[ Telegraph Clicking ]

379
00:28:10,190 --> 00:28:14,486
N-U-P-T.
Yeah. What else?
Shut up!

380
00:28:14,486 --> 00:28:17,197
Well, you don't have to
eat my head off.
Shut up!

381
00:28:17,280 --> 00:28:20,283
What's the matter with you?
Your wife havin' triplets or somethin'?

382
00:28:20,367 --> 00:28:23,495
The Japs just attacked Honolulu.
Bombed Pearl Harbor.

383
00:28:24,662 --> 00:28:26,581
Holy smokes!

384
00:28:26,665 --> 00:28:30,877
[ Bugle Call ]

385
00:28:30,960 --> 00:28:33,963
{y:i}[ Air Raid Sirens Blaring ]

386
00:28:36,966 --> 00:28:39,886
[ Air Raid Siren Continues ]

387
00:29:05,662 --> 00:29:08,164
Everything all set, Probenzki?

388
00:29:08,289 --> 00:29:12,794
You know, Lieutenant, airplanes,
they are for sure like women--

389
00:29:12,877 --> 00:29:16,881
sometimes good, sometimes bad,
sometimes you--you can't tell.

390
00:29:16,881 --> 00:29:20,385
Well, I'll take a chance on this one.
You're the best mechanic I've ever met.

391
00:29:20,468 --> 00:29:22,387
Thank you.
You're Russian, aren't you?

392
00:29:22,470 --> 00:29:24,973
No, Lieutenant. Polish.

393
00:29:24,973 --> 00:29:29,185
A Pole, huh? What on earth
got you into the Marine Corps?

394
00:29:29,269 --> 00:29:33,189
Well, I had my wife
and two children.

395
00:29:33,273 --> 00:29:35,358
They were in Warsaw.

396
00:29:35,483 --> 00:29:38,486
{y:i}[ Man ]
{y:i}Ready on number five.
Number five all set.

397
00:29:38,570 --> 00:29:41,865
You must be glad, Lieutenant,
you are not married.

398
00:29:41,865 --> 00:29:44,784
Probenzki,
my wife's at Pearl Harbor.

399
00:30:01,760 --> 00:30:05,388
Everything in order, gentlemen?
I was just hearing
the doctor's plans, sir.

400
00:30:05,472 --> 00:30:09,392
Emergency stations have been set up
at all key positions, sir.
Very good. How about you, Patrick?

401
00:30:09,559 --> 00:30:12,062
Four planes in the air, sir.
The other eight in reserve.

402
00:30:12,187 --> 00:30:14,481
There'll always be
four aloft?
That's right, sir.

403
00:30:14,564 --> 00:30:16,983
What have you been able
to do about the civilians?

404
00:30:17,067 --> 00:30:20,487
I've ordered them to take cover
in the slit trenches wherever possible.
Good.

405
00:30:20,570 --> 00:30:23,198
I'd like to see
those stations, Doctor.
Aye, aye, sir.

406
00:30:23,281 --> 00:30:27,077
That blasted air raid alarm again!
It's got my men running around
like gophers!

407
00:30:27,160 --> 00:30:30,789
The major will take care
of you, McCloskey.
That's the man I want to see!

408
00:30:32,582 --> 00:30:34,584
You got a piece of paper?

409
00:30:34,667 --> 00:30:37,879
You can have my resignation.
You wanna run my job?
Well, run it.

410
00:30:37,963 --> 00:30:42,384
I'm afraid that won't be
quite practical at the moment
for either one of us, McCloskey.

411
00:30:42,467 --> 00:30:46,262
Why not?
The Japs have just bombed
Pearl Harbor.

412
00:30:47,889 --> 00:30:51,893
Say that again.
The Japs have just bombed
Pearl Harbor.

413
00:30:51,976 --> 00:30:55,897
The Pan American Clipper will take off
as soon as Commander Roberts
deems it advisable,

414
00:30:55,980 --> 00:30:58,066
and there'll be
a place on it for you.

415
00:30:58,191 --> 00:31:01,486
In the meantime,
find yourself some shelter
and stay out of the way.

416
00:31:01,569 --> 00:31:04,989
All right, Patrick.
I'll take a look at your situation.
Yes, sir.

417
00:31:18,086 --> 00:31:20,088
Hiya, guys.

418
00:31:20,088 --> 00:31:23,466
Hey, Johnny, don't look now,
but I think we got a fifth columnist.

419
00:31:23,466 --> 00:31:26,886
Naw, he ain't no fifth columnist.
Not with that hat, he ain't.

420
00:31:26,970 --> 00:31:30,181
Run along, sonny. No tramps,
agents or peddlers allowed.

421
00:31:30,265 --> 00:31:34,185
Aw, lay off me, will ya, fellas?
I was just passin' time
till the Clipper leaves.

422
00:31:34,269 --> 00:31:36,896
I was wonderin' how your new
partner was makin' out, Joey.

423
00:31:36,896 --> 00:31:38,982
Don't worry about me.
I'm doin' all right.

424
00:31:39,065 --> 00:31:42,068
Yeah? Well, pick up that
ammunition chest, then.
Oh, yes, sir. Yes, sir.

425
00:31:42,193 --> 00:31:46,698
[ Laughs ]
All right, Randall.
On your way. On your way.

426
00:31:46,698 --> 00:31:50,577
Are you speakin' to me?
Yeah, I'm speakin' to you.
On your way.

427
00:31:50,577 --> 00:31:53,872
Beat it, gyrene, before I take a poke
at that thing you call a face!

428
00:31:53,872 --> 00:31:56,583
You're talkin' to a civilian, see!
Well, that's just it, buddy.

429
00:31:56,666 --> 00:31:58,793
Civilians in the slit trenches.
Major Caton's orders.

430
00:31:58,877 --> 00:32:01,087
[ Laughing ]
On your way.

431
00:32:01,171 --> 00:32:03,298
Take good care of that
civilian, Sarge.

432
00:32:03,381 --> 00:32:07,385
And don't let nothin' happen
to that elegant hat!
[ Laughing ]

433
00:32:08,470 --> 00:32:10,472
Enemy planes!

434
00:32:12,891 --> 00:32:17,896
Enemy planes sighted!
Enemy planes bearing southwest!

435
00:32:17,979 --> 00:32:20,482
[ Air Raid Siren Blaring ]

436
00:32:20,690 --> 00:32:23,693
{y:i}[ Bugle Call ]

437
00:32:36,581 --> 00:32:40,794
So you stopped playin' soldier.
Yeah, and look what it got me.

438
00:32:40,877 --> 00:32:42,963
Into the trench there!

439
00:32:43,088 --> 00:32:44,964
{y:i}[ Air Raid Siren Continues ]

440
00:33:37,267 --> 00:33:39,686
I have Lieutenant Cameron now, sir.

441
00:33:43,064 --> 00:33:46,359
Enemy fight attack with force.
Twenty-four planes.

442
00:33:46,484 --> 00:33:49,195
Twenty-four planes.
Attack as you see fit.

443
00:33:49,195 --> 00:33:51,573
Roger. Wilco.

444
00:33:51,573 --> 00:33:53,575
Four against 24.

445
00:33:53,575 --> 00:33:57,370
Just our luck they'd be
on the south leg of the patrol.

446
00:33:57,495 --> 00:34:02,167
Section one. Course: 3-5-0.

447
00:34:02,292 --> 00:34:04,961
Altitude: 25,000.

448
00:34:58,890 --> 00:35:01,476
We need that mortar.
Come on. Let's get it!
Okay.

449
00:35:01,559 --> 00:35:03,562
Sprint!

450
00:35:24,165 --> 00:35:27,293
Get to Caton! See if he
can spare a fire detail!

451
00:35:27,293 --> 00:35:29,295
Aye, sir.

452
00:35:34,676 --> 00:35:37,595
Stretcher bearers!
Stretcher bearers!

453
00:35:45,770 --> 00:35:49,065
[ Laughing ]
What are you laughin' at?

454
00:35:49,190 --> 00:35:52,193
Smacksie's hat.
Here he comes!

455
00:36:21,264 --> 00:36:25,185
Prepare to engage.
Prepare to engage.

456
00:36:25,185 --> 00:36:27,687
Prepare to engage. Roger.

457
00:36:34,194 --> 00:36:36,071
[ Shouts In Japanese ]

458
00:38:51,873 --> 00:38:54,459
All right, boys.
This is where we get off.

459
00:38:54,584 --> 00:38:57,962
Back home now.
Vector: starboard 1-8-0.

460
00:39:08,264 --> 00:39:12,060
Parker?
{y:i}Everything's all right, Major.

461
00:39:22,779 --> 00:39:24,697
Reporting, sir.

462
00:39:28,284 --> 00:39:33,290
This is the room where we entertained
those peace boys, isn't it?

463
00:39:33,373 --> 00:39:35,291
{y:i}[ Caton ]
{y:i}Yes, sir.

464
00:39:36,960 --> 00:39:39,170
Seems like a long time ago.

465
00:39:39,295 --> 00:39:43,383
{y:i}Doesn't it?
Yes, sir.

466
00:39:45,093 --> 00:39:50,390
I take back that toast I gave
to His Imperial Majesty.

467
00:39:55,395 --> 00:39:57,272
Major.

468
00:40:02,277 --> 00:40:05,697
Squadron communication.
Squadron communication.

469
00:40:05,780 --> 00:40:07,782
Go ahead.

470
00:40:07,866 --> 00:40:09,868
Reporting from Peel, sir.

471
00:40:09,993 --> 00:40:13,079
Lots of near misses, but
the Clipper wasn't damaged, sir.

472
00:40:13,163 --> 00:40:15,081
That's some help, anyhow.

473
00:40:21,671 --> 00:40:24,382
Orderly!
Yes, sir?

474
00:40:24,382 --> 00:40:29,262
Advise Dr. Parkman it'll be necessary
to evacuate his emergency hospital
as soon as possible.

475
00:40:29,262 --> 00:40:31,765
Aye, aye, sir.
Hello, Lewis, Patrick.

476
00:40:31,890 --> 00:40:34,684
We've got to get Dr. Parkman
and his people underground.

477
00:40:34,684 --> 00:40:38,480
This has been a checkerboard
bombing, and that sort of stuff
is no respecter of hospitals.

478
00:40:38,563 --> 00:40:41,983
Lewis, suppose you pick a good
spot and detail a work party.

479
00:40:42,067 --> 00:40:45,070
Aye, sir.
Patrick, how'd you make out
with your outfit?

480
00:40:45,195 --> 00:40:47,572
Twenty-three wounded,
seven killed, sir.

481
00:40:47,697 --> 00:40:51,785
Seven planes out of commission.
All the oil and gasoline
on the field destroyed.

482
00:40:51,868 --> 00:40:53,787
Even the big tanks?
That's right, sir.

483
00:40:53,870 --> 00:40:56,873
That's not so good.
How did the defense
battalion make out, sir?

484
00:40:56,998 --> 00:40:59,167
Not bad, considering
the strafing we got.

485
00:40:59,292 --> 00:41:01,795
You'll have to admit they did
a pretty thorough job of it.

486
00:41:01,878 --> 00:41:04,964
With mathematical precision,
square yard by square yard.

487
00:41:05,090 --> 00:41:08,760
When they attack again,
I have the feeling they won't
bomb the same square twice.

488
00:41:08,885 --> 00:41:13,181
So it's up to us to move
our guns, equipment and supplies
to the areas already bombed.

489
00:41:13,264 --> 00:41:16,476
I suggest you follow the same
procedure with your planes.
Aye, aye, sir.

490
00:41:16,559 --> 00:41:20,563
Patrick! You and your lads
have done a fine job.
We're proud of you.

491
00:41:20,688 --> 00:41:22,690
Thank you, sir.
Keep pitching.

492
00:41:22,690 --> 00:41:25,193
Aye, sir.
Captain Gordon
of the Clipper, sir.

493
00:41:25,276 --> 00:41:27,988
Oh, come in, Captain.
My name's Caton.
{y:i}How do you do, sir?

494
00:41:28,071 --> 00:41:30,782
Sorry we had to meet under
such unpleasant circumstances.

495
00:41:30,865 --> 00:41:32,992
You about ready to take off?
With your permission, sir.

496
00:41:33,076 --> 00:41:37,497
I don't see anything to hold you,
unless our Japanese friends pay us
another visit before you get away.

497
00:41:37,580 --> 00:41:41,376
All your passengers aboard?
They should be by now, sir.
They were boarding when I left.

498
00:41:41,376 --> 00:41:44,295
Well, good luck
and happy landings.
Thank you, sir.

499
00:41:44,379 --> 00:41:47,590
[ Whistling ]
Here, Skipper.

500
00:41:49,175 --> 00:41:51,386
Here, Skip.

501
00:41:51,469 --> 00:41:53,680
Come on, girl.

502
00:41:53,763 --> 00:41:56,182
Skipper, where are you?

503
00:41:56,266 --> 00:41:58,393
Here, Skip.

504
00:41:58,393 --> 00:42:01,980
Skipper. Skipper, you in there?

505
00:42:01,980 --> 00:42:04,190
Come on. Come on.
Get on the Clipper.

506
00:42:04,190 --> 00:42:06,693
You ain't seen that dog
around anyplace, have you?

507
00:42:06,776 --> 00:42:10,280
Never mind the dog. Get going.
That's funny. I ain't
seen her since the attack.

508
00:42:10,280 --> 00:42:12,782
Listen, you big dope!
The Clipper's waiting.
You're holding up the parade.

509
00:42:12,866 --> 00:42:15,160
Don't crowd me, will ya!

510
00:42:15,160 --> 00:42:18,788
Get on that Clipper and
get on it fast. That's an order.
I'll get on when I'm good and ready.

511
00:42:18,872 --> 00:42:22,375
And don't you give me no orders.
I'm a civilian, see!

512
00:42:22,375 --> 00:42:24,586
Bill, Joe, come here.

513
00:42:26,463 --> 00:42:29,966
Take this civilian
and toss him aboard the Clipper.

514
00:42:32,385 --> 00:42:34,471
Go on, get going.

515
00:42:34,471 --> 00:42:37,599
Oh, boy, oh, boy.
Come on, boys.

516
00:42:37,599 --> 00:42:40,268
Come and get it.
Come on.

517
00:42:40,685 --> 00:42:43,271
According to facts given me
by Corporal Goebbels, sir,

518
00:42:43,396 --> 00:42:46,483
the accused refused
to get aboard the Clipper, spoke
disrespectful to Corporal Goebbels...

519
00:42:46,566 --> 00:42:50,362
and assaulted First Class
Privates Bennett and Richmond,
causing them grievous bodily harm.

520
00:42:50,487 --> 00:42:53,698
To say nothing of what
he did to me, sir.
Silence, Corporal.

521
00:42:53,782 --> 00:42:56,159
Well, Randall, what have you
got to say for yourself?

522
00:42:56,284 --> 00:43:00,789
Well, sir--
It's these clothes, sir.
{y:i}What?

523
00:43:00,872 --> 00:43:04,167
Well, since I've been wearing them,
I don't seem to have no control.

524
00:43:04,292 --> 00:43:06,169
{y:i}Control?
Over my emotions.

525
00:43:08,296 --> 00:43:11,758
Randall, if my memory
serves me correctly,

526
00:43:11,883 --> 00:43:14,969
weren't you before me on
a similar charge back in Shanghai?

527
00:43:14,969 --> 00:43:17,097
{y:i}- No, sir.
- No?

528
00:43:17,180 --> 00:43:21,393
No, sir. That time it was the captain
of that Italian gunboat.

529
00:43:21,393 --> 00:43:24,687
Remember, the-- the one
with the long whiskers?

530
00:43:26,898 --> 00:43:28,983
Oh, yes, I remember now.

531
00:43:29,067 --> 00:43:31,987
- You did a pretty good job on him.
- Oh, thank you, sir.

532
00:43:35,198 --> 00:43:39,994
Uh, sir, if it's all the same to you,
I'd like to make the same request
I made then.

533
00:43:40,078 --> 00:43:42,163
To ship over?
Yes, sir.

534
00:43:42,289 --> 00:43:45,375
Randall, as man to man,
I congratulate you on your decision.

535
00:43:45,458 --> 00:43:48,378
But as your commanding officer,
I can tell you now--

536
00:43:48,378 --> 00:43:51,172
Since the beginning of hostilities,
you've never been out.

537
00:43:51,297 --> 00:43:53,300
You're a marine
for the duration.

538
00:43:53,383 --> 00:43:55,969
If you'd gotten aboard the Clipper,
they would have told you.

539
00:43:56,094 --> 00:43:58,096
Now I have a request to make.
Yes, sir?

540
00:43:58,179 --> 00:44:00,765
Burn that dogcatcher's outfit
and get back into your uniform!

541
00:44:00,974 --> 00:44:03,059
Sergeant, post him for duty.
That's all.

542
00:44:03,184 --> 00:44:06,563
Left face. Left face!
Forward march!

543
00:44:08,773 --> 00:44:10,692
That's all, Corporal.

544
00:44:15,488 --> 00:44:17,574
Mr. Hogan, sir.
Oh, hello, Hogan.

545
00:44:17,699 --> 00:44:20,076
Hello, Major.
I've brought my report.

546
00:44:20,076 --> 00:44:22,162
Not so good.

547
00:44:22,162 --> 00:44:23,997
Any further instructions?

548
00:44:24,080 --> 00:44:26,583
No.

549
00:44:26,583 --> 00:44:29,961
Just tell the rest of your men
to stay under cover, what's left of it.

550
00:44:30,086 --> 00:44:32,172
We'll get it again.
How soon? I don't know.

551
00:44:32,297 --> 00:44:35,884
Yes, sir.
Oh, by the way, did your
Mr. McCloskey get off on the Clipper?

552
00:44:35,967 --> 00:44:38,178
As far as I know.

553
00:44:38,261 --> 00:44:41,264
Oh, so you didn't leave after all?
Thought I was gonna
run out on you?

554
00:44:41,389 --> 00:44:44,559
Well--
Well, I was,
but I changed my mind.

555
00:44:46,478 --> 00:44:49,063
McCloskey,

556
00:44:49,189 --> 00:44:51,858
I'm glad you're staying.
Why?

557
00:44:51,983 --> 00:44:54,986
We need a man like you.
Good.

558
00:44:54,986 --> 00:44:57,489
Give me a gun.
No.

559
00:44:57,572 --> 00:45:00,492
You can be more valuable than that.
What do I do?

560
00:45:00,575 --> 00:45:03,870
Dig. Dig holes, lots of them,

561
00:45:03,995 --> 00:45:06,998
revetments for our planes,
shelter trenches.

562
00:45:07,165 --> 00:45:09,793
You'd better start
by digging a big one--

563
00:45:13,880 --> 00:45:18,385
one big enough to hold all the
casualties in our emergency hospital.

564
00:45:18,468 --> 00:45:20,678
Consider it done.

565
00:45:23,598 --> 00:45:26,476
[ Bugle Call ]

566
00:45:45,578 --> 00:45:50,291
Hard at it?
Running out of spare parts, sir,
so we're rolling our own.

567
00:45:50,375 --> 00:45:54,462
Just thought I'd drop in,
see how you were doing.

568
00:45:54,587 --> 00:45:57,173
Oh, Major Caton.
Orderly brought a signal over for you.

569
00:45:57,173 --> 00:45:59,175
Thank you.

570
00:46:02,470 --> 00:46:04,973
How's the rest of the world doing?

571
00:46:05,098 --> 00:46:07,058
Not so good.

572
00:46:10,562 --> 00:46:12,689
Cameron.
Yes, sir?

573
00:46:20,780 --> 00:46:23,074
Sit down.

574
00:46:25,368 --> 00:46:29,789
Cameron, I've got some bad news.
Yeah, I heard about it, sir.

575
00:46:29,873 --> 00:46:33,585
What?
You mean about Commander Roberts.
I've heard he's in pretty bad shape.

576
00:46:33,668 --> 00:46:38,465
It's not the commander. It's your wife.
She was killed in the bombing
at Pearl Harbor.

577
00:46:56,858 --> 00:46:59,861
I know there's nothing I can say
that will comfort you.

578
00:47:02,280 --> 00:47:06,076
You know, Cameron,
memories are funny things.

579
00:47:06,159 --> 00:47:08,078
They mold a man.

580
00:47:09,579 --> 00:47:11,998
From the time a man
can remember,

581
00:47:11,998 --> 00:47:15,460
his main memories are
those given to him by women--

582
00:47:15,585 --> 00:47:19,172
his mother, his sisters,

583
00:47:19,297 --> 00:47:22,259
his first sweetheart,

584
00:47:22,384 --> 00:47:24,594
his wife.

585
00:47:24,677 --> 00:47:26,888
Even those women
he might like to forget,

586
00:47:26,971 --> 00:47:30,392
even they give him memories
that might help sometime.

587
00:47:33,478 --> 00:47:36,564
No, there's nothing I can say
that will comfort you.

588
00:47:38,692 --> 00:47:42,988
You're like me now--
a man with a memory,

589
00:47:42,988 --> 00:47:45,198
But we're not alone.

590
00:47:45,198 --> 00:47:48,493
In this war, in any part of the world
wherever they've dropped
a stick of bombs,

591
00:47:48,576 --> 00:47:50,870
they've made thousands like us--

592
00:47:50,996 --> 00:47:54,666
men without wives,
without children,

593
00:47:54,874 --> 00:47:58,461
without a single thing
they've ever loved or held dear.

594
00:47:58,586 --> 00:48:02,882
And for those men,
there's a job to do-- to fight,

595
00:48:02,966 --> 00:48:05,260
fight with guns and bayonets
and tanks...

596
00:48:05,385 --> 00:48:08,096
and ships and planes.

597
00:48:08,096 --> 00:48:12,267
Fight to destroy... destruction.

598
00:48:13,768 --> 00:48:16,396
We've got to destroy destruction.

599
00:48:16,479 --> 00:48:18,982
That's our job, Bruce.

600
00:48:41,796 --> 00:48:45,884
{y:i}[ Man ]
{y:i}Enemy fleet approaching.
{y:i}Some destroyers, light cruisers.

601
00:48:45,967 --> 00:48:50,388
Troop ships. Possible submarines.

602
00:48:50,472 --> 00:48:52,098
Bearing:

603
00:48:52,182 --> 00:48:55,977
1-3-0 true.

604
00:48:56,061 --> 00:48:57,687
Range:

605
00:48:57,770 --> 00:49:02,192
1-7-0-0-0.

606
00:49:02,275 --> 00:49:03,777
Range:

607
00:49:03,985 --> 00:49:08,198
1-7-0-0-0.

608
00:49:08,198 --> 00:49:11,493
About 10 miles.
Looks like they have
no intention of stopping.

609
00:49:11,576 --> 00:49:13,995
That's our job.
Sir?

610
00:49:19,793 --> 00:49:23,880
I'm going to try and pull
an old Chinese trick.

611
00:49:23,880 --> 00:49:25,882
Talker.
Yes, sir?

612
00:49:37,477 --> 00:49:41,564
Observation reports
smoke screen.

613
00:49:41,689 --> 00:49:43,692
{y:i}Smoke screen.

614
00:49:45,193 --> 00:49:48,780
Smoke screen, smoke screen.

615
00:49:48,780 --> 00:49:51,199
Wind force: two.

616
00:49:51,199 --> 00:49:55,996
Direction: 1-8-0 true.

617
00:49:56,079 --> 00:49:57,789
Range:

618
00:49:57,872 --> 00:50:02,877
1-5-0-0-0.

619
00:50:06,881 --> 00:50:08,883
Operator.
Yes, sir?

620
00:50:08,967 --> 00:50:11,594
Get me the observation tower.
Yes, sir.

621
00:50:14,889 --> 00:50:17,392
Observation Tower, sir.

622
00:50:17,475 --> 00:50:20,186
Major Caton here.
Vacate the tower immediately.

623
00:50:20,270 --> 00:50:22,897
Take up your secondary
battle posts. Right.

624
00:50:22,897 --> 00:50:24,482
Range:

625
00:50:24,566 --> 00:50:29,070
1-4-0-0-0.

626
00:50:37,495 --> 00:50:40,081
Orders have been executed, sir.

627
00:50:40,290 --> 00:50:42,959
All guns well concealed?
Yes, sir.

628
00:50:43,084 --> 00:50:45,587
Planes?
As much as possible, sir.

629
00:50:45,670 --> 00:50:47,672
All men under cover
and standing by?

630
00:50:47,797 --> 00:50:49,799
Yes, sir.
Thank you.

631
00:50:49,799 --> 00:50:53,261
Single enemy plane
approaching, sir.

632
00:50:53,386 --> 00:50:55,597
Reconnaissance, probably.

633
00:50:59,768 --> 00:51:03,480
I'm beginning to understand
the major's idea now.

634
00:51:03,563 --> 00:51:06,858
Warn our men again
that they must stay under cover.
Yes, sir.

635
00:51:19,579 --> 00:51:22,582
[ Speaking Japanese ]

636
00:51:38,973 --> 00:51:40,976
[Japanese ]

637
00:51:47,065 --> 00:51:50,986
Enemy changing formation.
Changing formation.

638
00:51:52,279 --> 00:51:55,698
Preparing to attack.
That's what they came for.

639
00:52:02,580 --> 00:52:04,791
They're certainly closing in.

640
00:52:04,874 --> 00:52:08,169
Looks like my Chinese trick
might have some success after all.

641
00:52:08,294 --> 00:52:10,296
They've fallen for it hook,
line and sinker.

642
00:52:14,884 --> 00:52:16,594
Range:

643
00:52:16,678 --> 00:52:20,598
9-0-5-0.

644
00:52:36,865 --> 00:52:40,368
Awful lot of money
being wasted around here.
What do you mean?

645
00:52:40,493 --> 00:52:44,789
The price of one of them shells
would set me and Myrtle up
pretty on a chicken ranch.

646
00:52:44,873 --> 00:52:47,792
I thought you were all set for hogs.
Nah, hogs is out.

647
00:52:47,876 --> 00:52:50,879
Why?
They stink!

648
00:52:56,092 --> 00:52:59,971
Range: 8-0-5-0.

649
00:52:59,971 --> 00:53:03,099
Range: 8-0...

650
00:53:03,183 --> 00:53:05,393
5-0.

651
00:53:10,482 --> 00:53:13,193
What's the big idea?
Why do we have to leave our gun?

652
00:53:13,193 --> 00:53:15,195
Don't ask me. I don't know.

653
00:53:17,364 --> 00:53:18,990
Range:

654
00:53:19,073 --> 00:53:22,160
7-0-5-0.

655
00:53:31,961 --> 00:53:34,673
Check the phone
and see if it's still working.

656
00:53:34,798 --> 00:53:37,592
Number three gun checking.
Number three gun checking.

657
00:53:37,676 --> 00:53:40,595
Yes, Number Three,
I can hear you.

658
00:53:40,678 --> 00:53:43,264
Communications are okay.
Trouble?

659
00:53:43,264 --> 00:53:45,266
Number three checking
communications, sir.

660
00:53:45,392 --> 00:53:47,769
It's working, all right.

661
00:53:47,894 --> 00:53:50,897
I hope they know
what they're doing.
{y:i}[ Bomb Whistling ]

662
00:53:52,482 --> 00:53:56,569
Range: 6-0...

663
00:53:56,695 --> 00:53:58,572
{y:i}5-0.

664
00:54:01,991 --> 00:54:06,162
{y:i}[ Explosions ]

665
00:54:06,162 --> 00:54:08,582
The major must want 'em to get
close enough to throw rocks at us.

666
00:54:08,665 --> 00:54:10,792
Those ain't no rocks
they're throwin', brother.

667
00:54:12,877 --> 00:54:17,090
Give me the range
every hundred yards.
Aye, aye, sir. Every hundred yards.

668
00:54:23,596 --> 00:54:26,766
International code pennant--
two hoists.

669
00:54:26,891 --> 00:54:29,769
Roger, Negat, George--

670
00:54:32,480 --> 00:54:37,485
Range: 5-4-0-0.

671
00:54:37,569 --> 00:54:39,988
Signal from the Japs, sir.
What is it?

672
00:54:40,071 --> 00:54:43,283
Will you surrender?

673
00:54:43,283 --> 00:54:46,494
We'll give them their answer
in a few moments. Thank you.

674
00:54:46,494 --> 00:54:51,291
Range: 5-3-0-0.

675
00:55:02,177 --> 00:55:04,763
Range: 5-2...

676
00:55:04,888 --> 00:55:07,098
0-0.

677
00:55:07,182 --> 00:55:11,686
Lewis, did you ever hear
of Colonel William Prescott?

678
00:55:11,770 --> 00:55:13,480
No, sir.

679
00:55:13,563 --> 00:55:16,775
Well, he was the gentleman
at the Battle of Bunker Hill who said,

680
00:55:16,858 --> 00:55:19,986
"Don't fire till you can see
the whites of their eyes."

681
00:55:20,070 --> 00:55:22,572
You know,
I've always remembered that.

682
00:55:22,572 --> 00:55:24,699
I'll certainly remember it
from now on.

683
00:55:24,783 --> 00:55:29,371
Range: 5-1-0-0.

684
00:55:34,459 --> 00:55:36,669
Might as well take a crack
at them right now.

685
00:55:36,795 --> 00:55:39,881
Wait a minute.
You heard the orders.
We're to hold our fire.

686
00:55:39,964 --> 00:55:42,175
I don't know what for.

687
00:55:42,259 --> 00:55:44,969
We'll never have
a better chance than now.

688
00:55:45,095 --> 00:55:48,098
If they get any closer,
they'll blow this island to bits.

689
00:55:48,181 --> 00:55:51,893
What do you care?
It ain't your island, is it?

690
00:55:58,566 --> 00:56:02,988
Range: 5-0-0-0.

691
00:56:03,071 --> 00:56:06,074
{y:i}[ Man ]
{y:i}Range:5-0...

692
00:56:06,074 --> 00:56:08,493
0-0.

693
00:56:14,958 --> 00:56:19,295
Range: 4-9-0-0.

694
00:56:26,886 --> 00:56:28,680
Number four gun.

695
00:56:29,764 --> 00:56:34,769
{y:i}Range:4-8-0-0.

696
00:56:34,769 --> 00:56:36,771
Range--

697
00:56:37,981 --> 00:56:42,485
Range: 4-8-0-0.

698
00:56:51,870 --> 00:56:56,291
Range: 4-7-0-0.

699
00:56:56,374 --> 00:56:58,293
Range:

700
00:56:58,376 --> 00:57:01,963
4-7-0-0.

701
00:57:07,594 --> 00:57:11,097
To all batteries.
To all batteries.

702
00:57:11,181 --> 00:57:14,768
Open fire.
Open fire! Yahoo!

703
00:57:14,893 --> 00:57:17,479
To your stations!

704
00:57:20,482 --> 00:57:22,359
Fire!

705
00:57:27,489 --> 00:57:29,866
[ Speaking Japanese ]

706
00:58:18,290 --> 00:58:21,167
[ Man Screaming ]

707
00:58:28,466 --> 00:58:32,762
We seem to have cut down
their firepower. Bruce, suppose
you go up and take a look.

708
00:58:32,762 --> 00:58:36,474
With the greatest of pleasure, Bill.
Probenzki, roll her out and wind her up!

709
00:58:48,987 --> 00:58:50,989
Boy, what a shellacking.

710
00:58:59,789 --> 00:59:02,292
Talker.
Yes, sir?

711
00:59:02,375 --> 00:59:04,961
To all batteries.
To all batteries.

712
00:59:05,086 --> 00:59:07,088
Cease firing.
Cease firing.

713
00:59:07,172 --> 00:59:10,258
Cease firing!
Cease firing!

714
00:59:11,885 --> 00:59:15,597
Plane number five reports.
That's Cameron.

715
00:59:15,597 --> 00:59:18,183
Plane number five reports.
What is it?

716
00:59:18,266 --> 00:59:21,186
Enemy eight-inch
gun cruiser sighted.

717
00:59:21,269 --> 00:59:26,691
Bearing: 2-3-0 true.

718
00:59:26,691 --> 00:59:29,778
Distance: about 15 miles.

719
00:59:29,861 --> 00:59:33,198
Fifteen miles.
Not so good.

720
00:59:33,281 --> 00:59:37,285
That's way beyond our range.
They can lay out there
and smear us at will.

721
00:59:58,598 --> 01:00:02,185
Strip off everything you can and
drain out all but 1 5 gallons of gas.

722
01:00:02,269 --> 01:00:06,773
But, Lieutenant, with only that
much gas, it will be impossible to--
You heard me. Get at it.

723
01:00:12,570 --> 01:00:15,990
Oh, hello, gentlemen.
Lieutenant Cameron
has a request to make, sir.

724
01:00:16,074 --> 01:00:18,993
Yes?
I think I can get that cruiser, sir.

725
01:00:20,078 --> 01:00:22,372
What?
Yes, sir.

726
01:00:22,497 --> 01:00:26,084
How do you propose to do it?
If I strip my plane to the bone
and limit the gas load,

727
01:00:26,167 --> 01:00:30,463
I can make a takeoff
with a double load of bombs,
enough to do the job, sir.

728
01:00:30,588 --> 01:00:34,259
If you get two direct hits.
I think I can, sir.

729
01:00:37,095 --> 01:00:39,889
Request granted.
Thank you, sir.

730
01:00:39,973 --> 01:00:41,975
I, uh--

731
01:00:58,199 --> 01:01:00,285
Good hunting, Bruce.

732
01:01:00,285 --> 01:01:02,287
Thank you, sir.

733
01:01:10,170 --> 01:01:12,881
Bombs all set, Probenzki?
Yes, Lieutenant.

734
01:01:12,964 --> 01:01:17,886
Two little Christmas presents.
One from you and
one from me, huh?

735
01:01:17,969 --> 01:01:20,263
Here goes the mail.

736
01:01:51,795 --> 01:01:54,464
[Japanese ]

737
01:01:59,093 --> 01:02:01,596
[Japanese ]

738
01:02:49,060 --> 01:02:50,770
[ Turrets Firing ]

739
01:02:56,693 --> 01:02:59,487
{y:i}[ Bullets Ricocheting ]

740
01:03:43,364 --> 01:03:47,160
Glad he made it.
And a sweet job it was too, sir.

741
01:03:47,285 --> 01:03:51,581
What did you do to the arm?
Oh, trying to salvage another engine.
It was a little hot.

742
01:03:51,665 --> 01:03:55,293
Where's your first aid pouch?
Uh, it's empty, sir.

743
01:03:55,376 --> 01:03:58,171
Well, we've been using 'em
plenty around here.
Here, let me have it.

744
01:04:12,477 --> 01:04:15,897
Excuse me, sir.
I want to be the first
to shake the big lug's hand.

745
01:04:24,572 --> 01:04:27,575
Captain.
You better don't go there.

746
01:04:27,575 --> 01:04:30,662
Huh?
You better don't go.

747
01:04:30,787 --> 01:04:32,789
He's dead.

748
01:04:33,790 --> 01:04:37,377
Patrick!
Carry on, Sergeant.

749
01:04:39,671 --> 01:04:44,175
The sergeant's right.
It's better that you don't see him.

750
01:04:44,259 --> 01:04:46,594
Let's have that arm.

751
01:04:47,679 --> 01:04:50,682
[ Taps ]

752
01:05:04,863 --> 01:05:07,574
This one isn't ready yet.
[ Mutters ]

753
01:05:07,699 --> 01:05:10,660
{y:i}[ Continues ]

754
01:05:23,882 --> 01:05:25,884
{y:i}[ Bugle Stops ]

755
01:05:41,191 --> 01:05:46,196
"Man that is born of a woman
hath but a short time to live
and is full of misery.

756
01:05:46,279 --> 01:05:49,282
He cometh up and is
cut down like a flower."

757
01:05:49,365 --> 01:05:51,576
[ Sniffles ]

758
01:05:54,996 --> 01:05:57,999
Here, son, you finish it.

759
01:05:59,959 --> 01:06:03,088
"He fleeth as it were a shadow...

760
01:06:03,171 --> 01:06:06,883
"and never continueth in one stay.

761
01:06:06,883 --> 01:06:09,886
"In the midst of life,
we are in death.

762
01:06:09,969 --> 01:06:14,182
"Of whom may we look
for succor but of thee, O Lord,

763
01:06:18,061 --> 01:06:20,980
"who for our sins are justly displeased.

764
01:06:21,064 --> 01:06:23,775
"Yet, O Lord, God mostly holy,

765
01:06:23,858 --> 01:06:29,197
"O Lord most mighty,
O holy and most merciful savior,

766
01:06:29,281 --> 01:06:33,284
"deliver us not unto
the bitter pains of eternal death.

767
01:06:33,368 --> 01:06:37,372
"Thou knowest, Lord,
the secrets of our hearts.

768
01:06:37,372 --> 01:06:40,667
{y:i}"Shut not thy merciful ears
{y:i}to our prayers,

769
01:06:40,667 --> 01:06:43,878
{y:i}"but spare us, Lord most holy,

770
01:06:43,962 --> 01:06:48,383
{y:i}"O God most mighty,
{y:i}O holy and merciful savior.

771
01:06:48,466 --> 01:06:50,969
"Thou most worthy judge eternal,

772
01:06:51,094 --> 01:06:53,972
"suffer us not at our last hour...

773
01:06:54,097 --> 01:06:58,059
for any pains of death
that fall upon thee."

774
01:07:02,772 --> 01:07:04,774
Lower away.

775
01:08:57,262 --> 01:08:59,264
You sent for me, sir?

776
01:08:59,389 --> 01:09:02,475
Yes, Lewis, I did.
Have a cigarette.

777
01:09:04,978 --> 01:09:07,897
You know,

778
01:09:08,064 --> 01:09:11,776
we've been getting it
pretty steady for some time now.

779
01:09:11,860 --> 01:09:14,571
I've got a hunch we're in
for a few hours breather.

780
01:09:14,696 --> 01:09:17,699
Your hunches are usually right, sir.

781
01:09:17,782 --> 01:09:20,660
I contacted a navy patrol plane.

782
01:09:20,785 --> 01:09:22,996
They're gonna take a chance
and come in.

783
01:09:23,079 --> 01:09:27,083
I hope they make it.
Yeah.

784
01:09:30,962 --> 01:09:33,381
How'd you like to be home
for Christmas?

785
01:09:36,593 --> 01:09:41,973
Christmas dinner in Honolulu
with your missus and the youngsters.

786
01:09:41,973 --> 01:09:45,894
How's it sound to you?
You know good and well
how it sounds.

787
01:09:45,894 --> 01:09:48,771
All right, get your gear together
and stand by.

788
01:09:48,897 --> 01:09:51,983
Not this marine, sir.
Thought you'd say that.

789
01:09:53,276 --> 01:09:56,362
For two weeks now,
we've engaged the enemy daily.

790
01:09:56,488 --> 01:09:58,865
We've learned a lot about his tactics.

791
01:09:58,865 --> 01:10:02,160
That's information the Navy Department
needs firsthand.

792
01:10:02,160 --> 01:10:04,788
Well, there's Patrick.
Why don't you send him?

793
01:10:04,871 --> 01:10:08,375
He's the only pilot I've got left.

794
01:10:08,458 --> 01:10:10,960
I'm sorry, sir. I'm staying.

795
01:10:12,962 --> 01:10:15,298
Captain Lewis, this is an order!

796
01:10:20,971 --> 01:10:23,473
Aye, aye, sir.

797
01:10:23,598 --> 01:10:28,061
Lewis. Here's my official report.

798
01:10:28,186 --> 01:10:31,981
I'm not very good at this sort of thing,
but I guess with what you can tell them,

799
01:10:32,065 --> 01:10:35,193
it'll give them a pretty good idea
of what's going on here.

800
01:10:35,193 --> 01:10:38,363
Yes, sir.
One more thing.

801
01:10:38,488 --> 01:10:41,074
I--

802
01:10:41,282 --> 01:10:43,994
Pete, will you do me
a personal favor?

803
01:10:47,497 --> 01:10:49,583
For my daughter.

804
01:10:51,376 --> 01:10:53,378
I'll see that she gets it.

805
01:10:53,461 --> 01:10:55,797
Well, so long, Pete.

806
01:11:32,375 --> 01:11:34,377
Patrick, sit down.

807
01:11:36,087 --> 01:11:38,173
Well, you look pretty solemn.

808
01:11:38,173 --> 01:11:40,592
Enemy again, sir,
approaching in force.

809
01:11:40,675 --> 01:11:43,386
Transports screened
by a strong escort.

810
01:11:43,470 --> 01:11:46,097
Position and bearing.

811
01:11:46,181 --> 01:11:50,977
Well, looks like our holiday's over.
[ Radio Buzzing ]

812
01:11:51,061 --> 01:11:54,981
Ordnance reports.
Ordnance reports.

813
01:11:55,190 --> 01:11:59,861
Fifty-caliber ammunition
is nearly exhausted.

814
01:11:59,986 --> 01:12:01,571
Talker.
Yes, sir?

815
01:12:01,696 --> 01:12:03,865
Machine gun officer.
Yes, sir.

816
01:12:06,076 --> 01:12:07,994
Machine gun officer.

817
01:12:08,078 --> 01:12:10,080
Machine gun officer.

818
01:12:12,999 --> 01:12:15,084
Major Caton here.

819
01:12:15,168 --> 01:12:17,170
Replace the 50s
with the 30 calibers.

820
01:12:17,295 --> 01:12:20,173
Follow plan "D."
Split the gun crews.

821
01:12:20,298 --> 01:12:24,761
Spare men to take up positions
in number one beach head lines.
Repeat, please.

822
01:12:24,886 --> 01:12:27,097
Plan "D," Wilco.
Right.

823
01:12:27,180 --> 01:12:30,183
If possible, relieve some of your men
and see that they get a square meal.

824
01:12:30,183 --> 01:12:32,894
They'll need it soon. Right.

825
01:12:38,358 --> 01:12:41,194
Hey, how'd you guys like to wrap yourself
around some real chow right now?

826
01:12:41,277 --> 01:12:44,280
What do you mean?
I work hard--
No hard feelings, cookie.

827
01:12:44,364 --> 01:12:48,994
I only meant that if I was back
in the States, out with a dame,

828
01:12:48,994 --> 01:12:52,581
sitting in some little café,
you know what I'd order?

829
01:12:52,664 --> 01:12:55,959
A great big juicy steak about
that wide and about that thick.

830
01:12:56,084 --> 01:12:58,878
With onions?

831
01:12:58,962 --> 01:13:03,299
Oh, yeah, with lots of onions.
I'd settle just to be back
in the States.

832
01:13:03,383 --> 01:13:05,385
I'd settle just to be with a dame.

833
01:13:06,678 --> 01:13:08,680
With a dame.

834
01:13:09,889 --> 01:13:12,475
Aw, what are we
talking about it for?

835
01:13:12,559 --> 01:13:14,478
That's all we can do.

836
01:13:14,561 --> 01:13:16,562
Hey, Smacksie.

837
01:13:23,862 --> 01:13:26,197
What's the matter?
I got a surprise for you.

838
01:13:26,281 --> 01:13:30,076
Yeah, but my chow's gettin' cold.
Look, this is better than chow.
Come on.

839
01:13:30,160 --> 01:13:32,370
What could be better than chow?
Lots of things.

840
01:13:32,495 --> 01:13:35,499
On this island?
All right,
so maybe it came from heaven.

841
01:13:35,582 --> 01:13:38,877
What are you talkin' about?
Never mind.
Come around here.

842
01:13:38,877 --> 01:13:41,796
All right.
Now, close your eyes.

843
01:13:41,796 --> 01:13:44,174
Aw!
Come here. Come here.
This is serious.

844
01:13:44,299 --> 01:13:46,593
Now, close your eyes.

845
01:13:48,261 --> 01:13:52,474
Well--
Now, if you had three wishes,
what would you wish for?

846
01:13:52,474 --> 01:13:55,977
Myrtle.
Aw, no, something
better than Myrtle.

847
01:13:55,977 --> 01:13:58,396
What could be better than Myrtle?
Lots of things.

848
01:13:58,479 --> 01:14:01,274
Yeah, how do you know?
All right, I was stationed
at Mare Island too.

849
01:14:01,399 --> 01:14:03,485
Come on. Close your eyes.

850
01:14:05,570 --> 01:14:07,989
Now, wish.

851
01:14:08,073 --> 01:14:10,492
No, it's still Myrtle.
One-track mind.

852
01:14:10,575 --> 01:14:14,287
Look, half right, close your eyes
and kneel down. Come on.

853
01:14:16,873 --> 01:14:19,667
Now, open 'em.
Skipper!

854
01:14:19,792 --> 01:14:23,296
{y:i}Yeah, and she's got
{y:i}the fleet with her too.
{y:i}[ Laughing ]

855
01:14:23,379 --> 01:14:26,091
{y:i}How do you suppose that happened?
{y:i}I don't know.

856
01:14:26,174 --> 01:14:28,593
Hey, Joe!
Joe, come on over here.

857
01:14:28,677 --> 01:14:31,096
Look what Skipper went and done.

858
01:14:32,681 --> 01:14:34,891
Ain't nature wonderful?

859
01:14:36,268 --> 01:14:38,478
Hey, triplets, huh?
Quadruplets.

860
01:14:38,562 --> 01:14:40,980
Good old Skipper.
I got dibs on this one.

861
01:14:41,064 --> 01:14:43,358
No, no, they're all ours.
Yeah, it's our dog, ain't it?

862
01:14:43,483 --> 01:14:45,360
Yeah, but I found 'em, didn't I?
Well, we got 'em.

863
01:14:45,485 --> 01:14:49,489
Oh, not this one, you ain't.
Who do they look like?

864
01:14:49,489 --> 01:14:52,993
Well, this one--
Skipper's the only dog
that's ever been on the island.

865
01:14:53,076 --> 01:14:55,078
Hey, that's right.

866
01:14:56,288 --> 01:14:58,874
Skipper!

867
01:14:58,874 --> 01:15:00,667
Where have you been?

868
01:15:00,792 --> 01:15:03,086
She ain't been able to be no place.

869
01:15:03,086 --> 01:15:07,590
Hey, fellas,
you remember that tanker
that pulled in here?

870
01:15:09,759 --> 01:15:12,971
Never mind, Skipper.
We still love you.
{y:i}[ Bugle ]

871
01:15:13,096 --> 01:15:16,266
General quarters!
Take it easy, bub.
I'll be back.

872
01:15:16,391 --> 01:15:20,061
Now, don't you worry
about a thing, Skipper.
We'll watch 'em, Skipper.

873
01:15:21,396 --> 01:15:23,273
Oh, gee, I feel good.

874
01:15:23,398 --> 01:15:25,275
Me too.
Let's go.

875
01:15:25,692 --> 01:15:28,361
{y:i}[ Air Raid Siren Wailing ]

876
01:15:33,783 --> 01:15:36,286
[Japanese ]

877
01:15:55,764 --> 01:15:58,391
There goes {y:i}Betsy.
There she goes is right.

878
01:15:58,391 --> 01:16:00,560
The last one we've got.
{y:i}[ Explosion ]

879
01:16:54,072 --> 01:16:55,991
{y:i}[ Turrets Firing ]

880
01:17:02,581 --> 01:17:04,499
[Japanese ]

881
01:17:09,587 --> 01:17:11,381
{y:i}[ Gunfire ]

882
01:17:46,374 --> 01:17:48,293
Contact the beach head line.

883
01:17:48,376 --> 01:17:50,587
Tell them to stand by to pick up
Captain Patrick.
Yes, sir.

884
01:18:14,694 --> 01:18:16,571
The dirty--
{y:i}[ Explosion ]

885
01:18:38,093 --> 01:18:40,095
Try and get some stretcher bearers.

886
01:18:52,774 --> 01:18:55,068
Battery commander reports.

887
01:18:55,193 --> 01:18:58,863
Battery commander reports
direct hit on number two gun.

888
01:19:05,996 --> 01:19:07,873
How's the ammunition
holding out?

889
01:19:07,998 --> 01:19:10,959
Well, I guess we've got enough
to get a couple of'em.
Swell. Good luck!

890
01:19:11,084 --> 01:19:14,671
Heil.
Who said that?

891
01:19:14,796 --> 01:19:17,382
Us. It was always us.

892
01:19:17,382 --> 01:19:20,677
You're not such a bad guy, Gus.
We figured we'd let you in on it.

893
01:19:26,182 --> 01:19:29,186
You still wish us that good luck?

894
01:19:29,269 --> 01:19:31,271
You betcha. Good luck.

895
01:19:51,291 --> 01:19:54,961
It won't be long now.
They're laying down a barrage.

896
01:19:56,588 --> 01:19:58,965
What are you doing,
praying or something?

897
01:20:03,762 --> 01:20:06,181
Yes, Corporal, I guess I was praying.

898
01:20:07,599 --> 01:20:11,478
That's all right, Tommy.
There's nothing wrong with praying here.

899
01:20:11,686 --> 01:20:13,563
There are no atheists in foxholes.
{y:i}[ Bomb Whistling ]

900
01:20:13,771 --> 01:20:17,192
{y:i}[ Explosion ]

901
01:20:19,694 --> 01:20:24,491
Ordnance reports.
Ordnance reports. Direct hit
on ammunition dump, sir.

902
01:20:24,574 --> 01:20:28,787
Another signal from the the enemy, sir.
They demand immediate surrender.

903
01:20:29,996 --> 01:20:32,999
Any answer, sir?
Yes.

904
01:20:32,999 --> 01:20:35,585
Tell them to come and get us.
Aye, aye, sir.

905
01:20:35,585 --> 01:20:37,587
Fire!

906
01:20:44,177 --> 01:20:46,096
Cease firing!

907
01:20:46,179 --> 01:20:48,181
[ Radio Buzzing ]

908
01:20:49,975 --> 01:20:52,561
Number one gun reports.

909
01:20:52,686 --> 01:20:56,898
Number one gun reports
breech mechanism failed.

910
01:20:59,692 --> 01:21:01,486
That's our last five-inch, sir.

911
01:21:10,078 --> 01:21:12,581
They've got the Pan American
Inn straddled, sir.
Thank you.

912
01:21:19,587 --> 01:21:21,798
Come on. Get out!
This place has been evacuated.

913
01:21:21,881 --> 01:21:23,758
Who says so?
I do.

914
01:21:23,883 --> 01:21:27,679
I'm stayin' right here, brother.
Me too. It's as safe
as any spot on the island.

915
01:21:28,680 --> 01:21:30,682
Get him out!

916
01:21:33,477 --> 01:21:36,896
{y:i}[ Explosions Continue ]

917
01:21:36,980 --> 01:21:39,774
{y:i}[ Bomb Whistling ]

918
01:21:49,284 --> 01:21:51,286
To all posts.

919
01:21:54,080 --> 01:21:57,083
To all posts.
To all posts.

920
01:21:57,083 --> 01:22:00,295
Stand by to repel landing parties.
Follow plan "G."

921
01:22:00,295 --> 01:22:04,174
Fire independently.
Stand by to repel landing parties.

922
01:22:04,299 --> 01:22:08,762
Follow plan "G."
Fire independently.
Fire independently.

923
01:22:39,167 --> 01:22:42,295
The enemy has landed
on two points, sir,
and gaining ground.

924
01:22:42,378 --> 01:22:44,964
I tried to get you on the phone
but couldn't.
Thank you.

925
01:22:52,264 --> 01:22:55,183
Emergency radio.
Can't raise anyone, sir.

926
01:22:55,267 --> 01:22:57,894
Keep tryin'.
Yes, sir.

927
01:22:57,978 --> 01:23:01,898
Emergency radio.
Emergency radio.

928
01:23:04,567 --> 01:23:07,195
Any luck?
{y:i}The lines are all dead, sir.

929
01:23:07,195 --> 01:23:09,197
Talker.
{y:i}Yes, sir?

930
01:23:09,197 --> 01:23:13,368
Will you try and get through
to radio with this?
I'll do the best I can, sir.

931
01:23:13,493 --> 01:23:16,162
Good luck, Tex.
Thank you, sir.

932
01:23:29,259 --> 01:23:31,261
Well, McCloskey,
how are things with you?

933
01:23:31,261 --> 01:23:35,473
I figure I've done everything
I could in my line.
I'd still like that gun.

934
01:23:39,060 --> 01:23:43,189
You know, I've been thinking along
those same lines myself.

935
01:23:45,066 --> 01:23:47,777
Suppose we go out
and find one together.

936
01:24:13,178 --> 01:24:15,180
Grenade!

937
01:24:26,274 --> 01:24:28,985
{y:i}[ Sergeant ]
{y:i}Cease firing!
{y:i}[ Second ] Cease firing!

938
01:24:28,985 --> 01:24:33,073
Well, that does it.
For a minute, I guess.

939
01:24:34,866 --> 01:24:38,662
You know, this is a pretty
good trench you guys dug.
Thanks.

940
01:24:44,292 --> 01:24:47,170
Cigarette?
Thanks.

941
01:24:53,176 --> 01:24:55,595
That's a pretty good arm
you've got too.

942
01:24:55,679 --> 01:24:58,473
It's been bended long enough.
[ Chuckles ]

943
01:24:58,473 --> 01:25:03,478
From the way you threw that,
I'd almost think you played football.

944
01:25:03,562 --> 01:25:06,189
Notre Dame, '28.

945
01:25:06,272 --> 01:25:08,858
V.M.I., '28.

946
01:25:10,360 --> 01:25:12,278
Twenty-eight.

947
01:25:16,491 --> 01:25:18,994
To your very good health, sir.

948
01:25:21,580 --> 01:25:24,166
Hey, Joe.
Huh?

949
01:25:24,166 --> 01:25:27,168
How many blondes
do you suppose there are
that we didn't get around to?

950
01:25:27,293 --> 01:25:30,463
[ Chuckles ]
Must be an awful lot of them.

951
01:25:30,463 --> 01:25:33,591
I sort of feel sorry for them.
Don't you?

952
01:25:33,675 --> 01:25:37,679
Oh, I don't know.
Only half of'em are missing anything.

953
01:25:37,679 --> 01:25:39,889
Aw, cut it out, will ya?

954
01:25:51,860 --> 01:25:54,696
Come on, Smacksie!

955
01:25:54,779 --> 01:25:57,365
{y:i}[ Gunfire ]

956
01:26:26,686 --> 01:26:29,981
Hey, Smacksie.
Hey, Smacksie!

957
01:26:41,368 --> 01:26:44,287
[ Beeping ]

958
01:26:44,371 --> 01:26:46,665
[Japanese ]

959
01:26:46,790 --> 01:26:49,083
Be with you in a minute.

960
01:26:56,758 --> 01:26:59,678
{y:i}[ Gunfire ]

961
01:27:10,980 --> 01:27:13,566
{y:i}[ Narrator ]
{y:i}These marines fought a great fight.

962
01:27:13,691 --> 01:27:16,694
{y:i}They wrote history.
{y:i}But this is not the end.

963
01:27:16,694 --> 01:27:19,572
{y:i}There are other leathernecks,
{y:i}other fighting Americans--

964
01:27:19,698 --> 01:27:21,658
{y:i}a hundred and forty million of them,

965
01:27:21,783 --> 01:27:27,164
{y:i}whose blood and sweat and fury
{y:i}will exact a just and terrible vengeance.

